12:45.806 --> 12:48.058
Also, my dad was a sociopath.

12:48.100 --> 12:49.101
Edie worshipped him.

12:49.143 --> 12:51.437
They'll have to get her
     out of here with a crowbar.

12:51.479 --> 12:53.147
Her and my nephew, Clive.

12:53.189 --> 12:54.899
She has a pupa?

12:55.232 --> 12:56.567
Did he know Newton?

12:56.609 --> 12:57.860
Uh, well, her pupa is 20.

12:57.860 --> 13:00.613
She had him at 16 in
    a desperate bid for autonomy.

13:00.654 --> 13:02.615
But listen, Newton's name
           cannot come up.

13:02.615 --> 13:04.533
Newton is why we are here.

13:04.533 --> 13:06.577
No. Your magical device
         is why we're here.

13:06.577 --> 13:09.413
The prototype was
        drained at Book Club.

13:09.455 --> 13:10.706
It will not work again.

13:10.748 --> 13:12.541
We are here because of
           Thomas Newton.

13:12.583 --> 13:15.252
No. Listen, you just-- You can't
      even say his name, okay?

13:15.252 --> 13:17.254
If my sister sniffs it out

13:17.296 --> 13:19.298
and knows that she has
            what we want,

13:19.298 --> 13:20.591
she won't give us the patent,
             which means

13:20.633 --> 13:22.259
you can't build
         your magic machine.

13:22.301 --> 13:24.804
So just don't say
           his name, okay?

13:31.060 --> 13:32.478
Hello. I'm Yatzin.

13:32.520 --> 13:33.896
Miss Flood is just
       finishing up her ride,

13:33.938 --> 13:36.440
but she'll meet you in the blue
   room, if you'll just follow me.

13:36.440 --> 13:38.484
Yeah, I...
         I know where it is.

13:54.083 --> 13:55.501
-Hatch.
               -Wyant.

13:56.126 --> 13:57.127
You're looking fit.

13:57.127 --> 13:58.504
This is Justin Falls.

13:58.504 --> 14:00.256
Our project engineer.

14:00.256 --> 14:03.717
And, uh, this, um,
           is Mr. Faraday.

14:03.759 --> 14:06.262
The gentleman
     you've been eager to meet.

14:06.262 --> 14:09.306
And this is my sister.
             Edie Flood.

14:09.348 --> 14:11.851
I saw this on the way here.

14:13.978 --> 14:15.980
Uh,
      this is Professor Woads.

14:15.980 --> 14:18.566
He chairs the physics department
        at Imperial College.

14:18.607 --> 14:20.568
And he's agreed to consult.

14:20.568 --> 14:24.196
Your post-doc work on fusion
    modeling was very innovative.

14:24.196 --> 14:25.281
Thank you.

14:25.322 --> 14:26.657
Hmm. Didn't quite bear out,
               did it?

14:26.657 --> 14:29.201
Perhaps the font
        didn't work for you.

14:30.202 --> 14:31.287
Clive!

14:31.328 --> 14:32.288
Uncle Hatch.

14:32.329 --> 14:34.415
Hey, buddy. 

14:34.415 --> 14:36.000
Oh, oh. How are the shingles?

14:36.041 --> 14:38.502
Do you know, I... I think
    I pooped when you hugged me,

14:38.502 --> 14:39.795
they hurt so bad, but...

14:39.837 --> 14:41.881
Um,
      you just take care of...

14:41.922 --> 14:43.382
-Oh, hello.
                -Hi.

14:43.424 --> 14:45.134
Didn't expect you, Clive.

14:45.134 --> 14:46.010
Well, stealth.

14:46.010 --> 14:47.469
Well,
      shall we all have a seat?

14:47.511 --> 14:50.180
-Oh, by all means.
     -Great. Thank you.

14:50.180 --> 14:51.515
Hey. Come on.

14:51.515 --> 14:54.268
-Let's sit down. Come on.

14:55.644 --> 14:58.230
I'd like to know
         exactly what it was

14:58.272 --> 14:59.607
you presented at Book Club.

14:59.607 --> 15:01.233
Uh, a prototype.

15:01.275 --> 15:02.985
For a fusion generator.

15:03.027 --> 15:05.821
A personal fusion generator
      that fits in your pocket,

15:05.821 --> 15:08.407
with the potential to turn
        a gram of clean fuel

15:08.449 --> 15:10.826
into 20,000 kilowatt
           hours of power.

15:10.826 --> 15:14.705
Uh, I'm sorry.
    So, this device could run...

15:14.705 --> 15:16.540
uh, Buckingham Palace

15:16.540 --> 15:19.209
on less than
       a gallon of tap water.

15:19.209 --> 15:20.502
-For...
              -A year.

15:20.544 --> 15:21.629
Well, can we see it?

15:21.670 --> 15:23.464
Uh, we can't. It's capacitated.

15:23.464 --> 15:25.716
-That's convenient.
      -Well, it's a prototype.

15:25.716 --> 15:28.385
It has design flaws
    the final product won't have.

15:28.427 --> 15:30.471
We need to build
        a sustainable version

15:30.512 --> 15:32.890
-that doesn't burn itself out.
           -If it's real.

15:32.932 --> 15:34.642
Why would it not be real?

15:35.809 --> 15:39.480
Mr. Faraday, you're something
    of a mystery in all of this.

15:39.480 --> 15:41.607
What is this?

15:41.607 --> 15:45.945
That's a sugar snap pea with
      salmon and cream cheese.

15:52.618 --> 15:55.579
So, uh, we already
          have term sheets

15:55.579 --> 15:58.415
from Microsoft,
         Apple and Samsung.

15:58.457 --> 15:59.792
I think it would be
         good to find a home

15:59.833 --> 16:02.419
where you wouldn't
        just be an algorithm.

16:02.461 --> 16:04.630
You know, we're family.

16:05.172 --> 16:06.173
Family.

16:06.215 --> 16:09.426
That's why I'm here
      instead of anywhere else.

16:09.468 --> 16:10.552
But we're gonna need to

16:10.594 --> 16:12.930
replicate the cell
          on a mass scale.

16:12.930 --> 16:14.139
And the US
       Department of Energy...

16:14.181 --> 16:15.766
-All right. Stop. Stop it.
   -...has the power to tie us up

16:15.808 --> 16:19.311
in regulatory scrutiny
          for two decades.

16:19.311 --> 16:21.313
But, since our father

16:21.313 --> 16:22.815
made an arrangement with them

16:22.815 --> 16:24.483
during his tenure as CEO--

16:24.483 --> 16:26.276
There's no confirmation of that.

16:26.318 --> 16:27.611
We need to buy into OriGen's

16:27.611 --> 16:29.697
legal clearances
         and infrastructure.

16:29.738 --> 16:32.074
You're our fastest route
        to the energy market.

16:32.116 --> 16:34.868
So, you're proposing
    a joint venture partnership.

16:34.910 --> 16:39.498
For which you'll retain
         15% of the company.

16:39.540 --> 16:43.419
You want us to
      hand over 85% of OriGen.

16:43.460 --> 16:45.045
15% of the world's
         next energy source

16:45.087 --> 16:48.632
is worth 100% more than anything
    in heaven and earth, Horatio.

16:48.674 --> 16:51.343
Now, I actually read
     my dad's pretentious books,

16:51.343 --> 16:52.761
so I can say stuff like that.

16:52.761 --> 16:55.556
This pretense is making me sick.

16:55.556 --> 16:58.142
I don't know this woman
         and this man is...

16:58.142 --> 17:01.478
Well, I don't know,
   maybe he's the one real thing,

17:01.478 --> 17:03.856
and he's playing
         for the wrong team.

17:03.856 --> 17:06.483
-Edie--
     -Who are you, Mr. Faraday?

17:06.525 --> 17:07.609
You're their last chance.

17:07.651 --> 17:10.362
I need to know you,
    or this isn't going to work.

17:11.822 --> 17:13.032
I...

17:13.615 --> 17:15.034
am...

17:17.619 --> 17:18.746
an immigrant.

17:18.746 --> 17:21.040
Then this isn't going to work.

17:21.707 --> 17:23.709
I want to know about
           Thomas Newton.

17:26.170 --> 17:26.962
I'm sorry?

17:27.004 --> 17:28.797
Your father took possession
           of his company.

17:28.839 --> 17:30.966
I want to know
        what happened to him.

17:31.008 --> 17:33.385
Why do you want to know
        about Thomas Newton?

17:33.427 --> 17:35.304
I have his music. 

17:35.345 --> 17:38.015
Music? Newton made music?

17:38.015 --> 17:41.560
Yeah. Uh,
    it's all on one of those, uh,

17:41.560 --> 17:44.438
World Enterprises
      recording sphere things.

17:44.480 --> 17:46.356
It's in my grandfather's study.

17:46.356 --> 17:47.733
What does it sound like?

17:47.733 --> 17:49.276
Emo whale?

17:50.652 --> 17:51.737
Take me there now.

17:51.737 --> 17:53.489
Yeah, I don't think
         now is the time...

17:53.530 --> 17:54.740
Take me there. Now.

17:54.782 --> 17:55.866
Yeah. Okay. 

17:55.908 --> 17:57.743
Clive. A word before you go.

18:02.998 --> 18:06.585
If you want to be invited to
   the grown-up's table next time,

18:06.585 --> 18:08.504
you will not fuck this up.

18:08.545 --> 18:10.422
I need to know
        everything about him.

18:10.464 --> 18:11.840
We need to know, Clive.

18:11.882 --> 18:14.551
Do whatever you have to
         to get him talking.

18:14.551 --> 18:16.804
Okay, yeah. 

18:16.804 --> 18:18.430
Wh-- Uh, what does that mean?

18:19.556 --> 18:21.517
Give him some of
        whatever's turned you

18:21.558 --> 18:23.977
into a sniffly
         little chatterbox.

18:24.019 --> 18:27.523
I don't care. It's your future
          as well as ours.

18:59.429 --> 19:01.473
Hello. Can I help you?

19:01.473 --> 19:03.976
Oh, I hope so. Um, I understand,

19:03.976 --> 19:07.312
uh, a part of your mission
       here is rehabilitation?

19:07.354 --> 19:08.522
Drug addiction?

19:08.564 --> 19:09.940
Yeah. Women only.

19:09.940 --> 19:10.941
Oh, yeah. Sure, sure.

19:10.983 --> 19:14.820
I just, um, my mother has...

19:16.196 --> 19:19.491
Look, I know I should've made
     an appointment. I'm just...

19:19.533 --> 19:21.034
I'm just at the end of my rope.

19:21.076 --> 19:23.453
I wasn't even planning
        on coming here today.

19:23.495 --> 19:24.621
It just sort of happened.

19:24.621 --> 19:27.457
Does that sound strange?

19:27.499 --> 19:29.835
Happens often.

19:31.336 --> 19:34.339
Most of the Oblates here
          are in recovery.

19:34.381 --> 19:35.174
Okay.

19:35.215 --> 19:37.843
Uh, except Sister Mary Lou.

19:37.843 --> 19:39.595
Well, she's taken final vows.

19:39.595 --> 19:40.429
I see.

19:40.429 --> 19:42.806
You know, a lot of us,
       we live on the outside,

19:42.806 --> 19:44.391
but we're affiliated.

19:45.517 --> 19:46.852
We live by the teachings.

19:46.894 --> 19:49.438
We work. We pray.

19:49.479 --> 19:51.190
-Hmm.
               -We...

19:51.857 --> 19:53.650
try to heal.

19:53.692 --> 19:55.694
We live simply in Christ.

19:55.736 --> 19:57.738
That is so great. 

19:57.779 --> 20:01.116
Chantal! Chantal,
      come help! It's a breech!

20:01.158 --> 20:02.701
Oh, that's Mary Lou!

20:03.702 --> 20:05.037
-Uh...
    -One of our cows is birthing.

20:05.037 --> 20:06.622
A breech requires
        a lot of strong arms.

20:06.663 --> 20:08.916
-We could use your help.
           -That's sweet.

20:08.957 --> 20:11.543
I am a river

20:11.585 --> 20:15.172
Flowing to the ocean

20:15.714 --> 20:18.759
I am a river...

20:18.759 --> 20:21.011
You gotta try
       and turn the calf, Jay.

20:21.053 --> 20:23.805
I am trying. I am trying,
          I don't know how.

20:23.805 --> 20:25.807
Yeah. Oh, you gotta
       get a hold of his legs

20:25.849 --> 20:26.808
and pull real hard.

20:26.850 --> 20:28.894
Someone else
        should be doing this.

20:28.936 --> 20:30.562
--Uh, Katie, hold the tail.

20:31.355 --> 20:32.564
Fuck.

20:32.606 --> 20:33.815
Cut the singing, girls.

20:33.857 --> 20:36.860
I am a river

20:36.902 --> 20:38.362
Cut it. Shut the fuck up.

20:39.321 --> 20:41.865
So, you gotta do
        one final pull, Jay.

20:41.907 --> 20:42.991
Okay. It's Clay.

20:43.033 --> 20:44.785
-Yeah. That's it.
   -I can't feel my arms. 

20:44.826 --> 20:46.828
She can. Okay, now,

20:46.870 --> 20:48.789
oh, Mommy,
      you're doing a good job.

20:48.830 --> 20:50.958
--I know, I know.

20:50.958 --> 20:53.710
-Hold the tail, Katie. Katie.

20:53.710 --> 20:54.878
Pull!

21:05.389 --> 21:06.932
Good. Oh.

21:06.932 --> 21:09.601
Oh, Jay. You'll be okay.

21:09.643 --> 21:12.437
You did awesome.

21:25.033 --> 21:28.495
Hey, that T-shirt really
      works on you. 

21:28.495 --> 21:30.706
Yeah.

21:30.747 --> 21:32.749
You all right?

21:32.749 --> 21:36.044
Oh, I'm great.
        That was... special.

21:36.086 --> 21:38.422
-It was great.
   -What can I do for you, kiddo?

21:38.422 --> 21:39.965
Oh, well...
       Um--

21:40.966 --> 21:42.968
Oh, call to prayer.
         Do you wanna come?

21:42.968 --> 21:46.263
No, no, no. I was just, um...

21:46.763 --> 21:48.181
I'm here about my mom.

21:48.181 --> 21:49.308
She's been...

21:49.308 --> 21:51.643
She's been going through
          some tough stuff.

21:52.561 --> 21:54.771
Your mom, huh?

21:54.813 --> 21:56.606
There's something going on
           with your mom?

21:56.606 --> 21:57.607
Yeah.

21:57.607 --> 21:58.859
Kiddo.

21:58.859 --> 22:01.069
I've been doing this
         a long time, okay?

22:01.069 --> 22:02.237
You know,
        working with addicts.

22:02.279 --> 22:05.866
I can usually
       tell when, you know...

22:05.866 --> 22:07.659
There may be something
        wrong with your mom,

22:07.701 --> 22:09.786
but that's not why you're here.

22:13.790 --> 22:15.709
Yeah, I'm here
        about Thomas Newton.

22:21.757 --> 22:23.342
Tommy?

22:38.899 --> 22:40.734
I think I know who you are.

22:42.694 --> 22:43.820
Who am I?

22:46.907 --> 22:50.869
I've been waiting 45 years.

22:50.911 --> 22:52.871
But I knew. You see, I knew.

22:53.997 --> 22:56.666
I knew, and...
      And I prayed that one day

22:57.125 --> 23:00.629
he would send me a sign.

23:00.629 --> 23:02.714
Oh, thank God.

23:03.173 --> 23:04.591
Oh, thank the Lord.

23:04.633 --> 23:06.218
Thank the Lord.

23:06.218 --> 23:08.428
Thank you, thank you, thank you.

23:13.350 --> 23:15.143
And what's
   the expected Q for the device?

23:15.143 --> 23:17.604
This isn't my specialty.

23:17.646 --> 23:18.522
What's a Q?

23:18.522 --> 23:22.067
It's the ratio of energy
      you get out of the device

23:22.109 --> 23:23.944
compared to what you put in.

23:23.985 --> 23:26.363
A Q of 1.0
         is the break even.

23:26.405 --> 23:28.824
To date, the best anyone's
            ever achieved

23:28.824 --> 23:30.283
is around 0.7.

23:30.283 --> 23:33.745
And we're projecting
        a Q of 100 to 10,000.

23:34.788 --> 23:36.289
Have you tested this equation?

23:43.213 --> 23:45.966
Oh, well, that's what
       lab work is for, right?

23:45.966 --> 23:47.884
Well, the probability
         of miscalculation--

23:47.884 --> 23:49.594
"The probability
         of miscalculation"?

23:49.636 --> 23:52.180
My goodness, wow.
      There speaks an academic.

23:52.222 --> 23:54.057
If you don't like the questions,
         go somewhere else.

23:54.099 --> 23:56.351
And if you don't like
 the answers, we absolutely will.

23:56.351 --> 23:58.562
I don't appreciate
       this person's arrogance

23:58.603 --> 24:01.314
in thinking he can take
    the human element out of it.

24:01.356 --> 24:03.066
If he'd ever been inside a lab,

24:03.108 --> 24:04.693
he'd know that's impossible.

24:09.197 --> 24:11.783
In science,
          everything is error

24:11.825 --> 24:13.034
until the day it isn't.

24:13.034 --> 24:14.661
Today is that day.

24:14.661 --> 24:16.663
Is it? Today?

24:16.663 --> 24:17.664
Lucky for you,

24:17.706 --> 24:20.876
since you've spent the last
   five years scrubbing bio-waste.

24:20.917 --> 24:22.085
Was that always the plan?

24:22.127 --> 24:24.129
MIT, grad school at 22,

24:24.171 --> 24:27.132
all to realize the dream of
     donning a plastic moon suit

24:27.174 --> 24:29.926
and shoveling shit
       all these years later.

24:29.926 --> 24:32.888
I googled.
      Help me fill in the gaps.

24:32.929 --> 24:34.764
Get your boy
          to mind the gaps.

24:34.764 --> 24:36.057
I don't work for you.

24:36.057 --> 24:37.058
Mm. Yet.

24:37.100 --> 24:40.020
You were given buckets
      of funding from the DOE.

24:40.061 --> 24:41.980
It's like they signed
         a check on Friday,

24:41.980 --> 24:43.857
but by Monday
        you no longer existed.

24:43.899 --> 24:45.358
Can you tell us why?

24:52.115 --> 24:54.284
Well, this is fun
     but let's get back to work.

24:54.326 --> 24:57.537
All right. Let's talk about
        the Coulomb barrier.

24:57.537 --> 24:59.623
The Coulomb barrier potential

24:59.664 --> 25:02.209
is just one part
           of the equation.

25:02.209 --> 25:04.127
-Are you okay?
            -Fine. Yeah.

25:04.127 --> 25:06.838
It's just, uh,
          one part of the--

25:10.008 --> 25:11.676
What is wrong with you?

25:13.803 --> 25:15.680
Um... 

25:18.934 --> 25:20.727
Can you give me
          a minute, please?

25:33.615 --> 25:34.658
No!

25:38.453 --> 25:39.538
Hey. Are you okay?

25:39.579 --> 25:43.166
Yeah. Um, yeah,
      this... This won't work.

25:43.208 --> 25:44.292
Do you need a break?

25:44.292 --> 25:47.003
No. I have to stop. I...
      I can't do it. I'm sorry.

25:47.045 --> 25:48.004
What are you talking about?

25:48.004 --> 25:49.214
You're the only one
          who can do this.

25:49.256 --> 25:53.343
Look. I have people I'm
    responsible for. I am sorry.

25:53.385 --> 25:54.928
Yeah, but I can't do
          this without you.

25:54.928 --> 25:56.263
Where's Faraday?

25:56.304 --> 25:58.557
He's in my dad's study,
          down by the lake.

26:05.313 --> 26:06.690
Hey, could you tell me how, uh,

26:06.731 --> 26:08.441
you and Thomas Newton
          knew each other?

26:08.483 --> 26:10.026
Yes.

26:10.068 --> 26:12.070
Oh, you know,

26:12.988 --> 26:17.242
Tommy was jealous
         of all our colors.

26:19.286 --> 26:23.248
We met when I was
      a hotel maid in Kentucky.

26:23.248 --> 26:26.334
And he changed
       everything in my world,

26:26.376 --> 26:27.544
then he disappeared.

26:27.544 --> 26:31.590
All I knew was that his
    company had moved to England.

26:32.215 --> 26:33.967
I followed. But, uh...

26:35.885 --> 26:37.304
I never found him.

26:37.345 --> 26:40.098
All I could feel
          was his absence,

26:40.140 --> 26:41.933
and that's still all I feel.

26:48.857 --> 26:51.985
Don't you-- Shouldn't
      you be wearing a kind of

26:51.985 --> 26:53.653
a helmet or...

27:00.160 --> 27:01.911
I couldn't speak.

27:01.953 --> 27:03.413
What are you doing there?

27:03.413 --> 27:05.123
Couldn't even say
         his name out loud.

27:05.123 --> 27:07.292
For 45 years,
         I couldn't confess.

27:07.292 --> 27:09.252
This is my time.

27:09.294 --> 27:12.005
This is my time for penance.

27:16.092 --> 27:17.135
Oh.

27:35.737 --> 27:38.990
So, this is
       my grandfather's study.

27:39.824 --> 27:41.201
And, yeah.

27:41.201 --> 27:43.370
That's Newton's music player.

27:43.370 --> 27:45.997
This place was forbidden
          when I was a kid.

27:45.997 --> 27:47.999
But I come here whenever I want.

27:47.999 --> 27:49.542
Where is Newton's music?

27:49.542 --> 27:51.795
You know, my mother is brusque

27:51.836 --> 27:55.382
to say the least,
        but she's not crazy.

27:55.382 --> 27:57.258
She believes it's impossible,

27:57.300 --> 28:00.720
impossible to make
 a prototype like this in secret.

28:00.762 --> 28:03.223
I don't share that perspective.

28:03.264 --> 28:05.016
Epinephrine.

28:05.183 --> 28:06.101
Fear.

28:06.101 --> 28:08.353
I smelled it in the blue room.

28:08.353 --> 28:09.813
As far as I am aware,

28:09.813 --> 28:12.399
humans do not
         eat their children,

28:12.399 --> 28:15.402
and yet you are
     very afraid of each other.

28:15.443 --> 28:16.486
Afraid of-- 

28:16.528 --> 28:17.821
Of each other.

28:17.862 --> 28:20.615
Why do you
          keep doing that?

28:20.615 --> 28:22.742
It's just something
        that I do. 

28:22.784 --> 28:25.245
-Is it a communication?
                -No.

28:25.245 --> 28:26.246
Who is it for?

28:26.246 --> 28:28.164
I can't con-- 

28:28.164 --> 28:29.624
Can't control it?
          Yet it is yours.

28:29.666 --> 28:33.169
You're
      actually making it worse.

28:33.169 --> 28:34.337
Why are you so afraid?

28:34.337 --> 28:36.172
Where is Newton's music?

28:36.172 --> 28:38.049
Why are you so afraid?

28:41.428 --> 28:43.096
I'm not anymore.

28:43.096 --> 28:45.056
Hot!

28:48.601 --> 28:52.313
Hot! Hot! Very hot!

28:52.355 --> 28:54.983
Don't bark at me.

28:55.024 --> 28:56.443
Am I talking loudly?

28:56.484 --> 28:58.153
Yes, you are.

29:08.371 --> 29:10.290
Where is Newton's music?

29:10.290 --> 29:13.460
Well, you have to have
          the music sphere.

29:13.501 --> 29:15.211
It looks like a little pinball.

29:15.253 --> 29:16.713
Where is the sphere?

29:16.755 --> 29:20.341
If you tell me where you
   come from, then I'll tell you.

29:20.383 --> 29:22.218
You have the sphere.

29:22.260 --> 29:23.219
No, I don't.

29:23.219 --> 29:24.387
You have to tell me
         where you're from.

29:24.387 --> 29:26.306
I can smell it on you.

29:26.306 --> 29:27.766
Jesus!

29:57.587 --> 30:01.466
He told me
       he had someone back home,

30:01.466 --> 30:03.968
a wife, and I didn't care.

30:04.469 --> 30:07.096
I couldn't stop myself.

30:07.096 --> 30:09.140
He was light as a feather.

30:09.182 --> 30:11.476
And I kept saying to myself,

30:11.476 --> 30:13.770
"He's in the wrong place."

30:14.062 --> 30:14.938
He's here, yes.

30:14.938 --> 30:18.149
But it's like
      he's waiting for a train.

30:18.191 --> 30:20.485
He's just waiting to leave.

30:27.367 --> 30:30.495
You know,
      I could run this company

30:30.537 --> 30:33.498
without my mother. We could.

30:33.498 --> 30:34.874
Stop talking.

30:34.916 --> 30:38.294
It's just making a lot of
         pretentious noises.

30:42.757 --> 30:44.509
It's a message...

30:46.386 --> 30:48.304
to his wife.

30:51.975 --> 30:53.184
To home.

30:56.688 --> 30:59.065
He's trying to tell her

31:00.942 --> 31:02.193
goodbye.

31:02.569 --> 31:05.905
I'm falling into darkness.

31:09.492 --> 31:12.871
I keep waiting
         to hit the bottom,

31:13.580 --> 31:18.042
to be unable to remember you.

31:19.085 --> 31:20.378
But I do.

31:21.754 --> 31:23.923
-I remember you.
          -I remember you.

31:24.757 --> 31:26.175
I hold you in my fist.

31:26.175 --> 31:28.094
I hold you in my fist.

31:28.094 --> 31:31.598
-I can still say your name.
     -I can still say your name.

31:31.598 --> 31:33.975
But they're prying open
        my fingers one by one.

31:33.975 --> 31:36.853
But they're prying open
       my fingers one by one.

31:37.395 --> 31:39.355
Maybe forgetting
           will be a relief.

31:39.355 --> 31:41.941
Maybe forgetting
          will be a relief.

31:44.152 --> 31:47.697
I had a last view of

31:47.697 --> 31:51.618
where the ocean used
       to be before I left home.

31:51.618 --> 31:54.287
I didn't know then
        what I was looking at.

31:54.329 --> 31:56.581
But I was looking...

31:57.290 --> 31:59.292
...at the end of me.

32:00.960 --> 32:03.546
He said
      he had to get back to her

32:03.588 --> 32:05.715
before he lost himself.

32:05.757 --> 32:07.300
And he came to me because

32:07.300 --> 32:09.218
I was supposed to know better.

32:09.218 --> 32:10.637
And in my heart I did.

32:10.678 --> 32:12.263
-Oh, fuck.
         -I thought the way

32:12.305 --> 32:13.389
to love someone

32:13.389 --> 32:15.433
was to give them gin,

32:16.392 --> 32:19.520
because I drank gin.

32:19.520 --> 32:22.732
I made him drink gin, too.
         And it drowned him.

32:22.732 --> 32:25.360
I loved him,
       and I made him love me

32:25.360 --> 32:27.946
and need me
       and it just broke him.

32:27.946 --> 32:30.823
It broke his heart.
         It made him crazy.

32:30.823 --> 32:33.117
You can break...
     You can break their hearts?

32:33.159 --> 32:35.495
What? They?

32:35.536 --> 32:37.580
Dear God, oh, no.

32:37.580 --> 32:39.207
Is there another one?

32:39.207 --> 32:40.083
Is that why you're here?

32:40.124 --> 32:43.002
Oh, Jay,
    Jay, you have to protect him.

32:43.002 --> 32:45.672
Don't let him need anyone.
           He's a miracle!

32:45.713 --> 32:48.466
But miracles
        are like nightmares.

32:48.508 --> 32:50.593
You see, either God
       makes you strong enough

32:50.635 --> 32:53.054
to face them or he doesn't.

32:53.096 --> 32:53.846
I wasn't.

32:53.888 --> 32:56.724
You've got to protect him
         or he'll go insane.

32:56.724 --> 32:58.810
He'll go insane.
           Do you hear me?

32:58.810 --> 33:00.937
-Yeah. Yeah. I hear you.
             -Yes. Good.

33:00.937 --> 33:02.271
-I hear you.
               -Good.

33:02.271 --> 33:02.939
Yeah.

33:02.981 --> 33:05.400
My mind
           is slipping away.

33:05.400 --> 33:09.028
Help me
          remember your name.

33:09.737 --> 33:11.948
Help me. Help me.

33:11.990 --> 33:15.952
Help me.
      Help me remember your name.

33:16.703 --> 33:18.329
It's gone.

33:20.331 --> 33:22.208
You're becoming a memory.

33:44.897 --> 33:47.025
Tell my wife.

33:53.823 --> 33:57.035
Tell my wife
        I love her very much.

33:58.369 --> 34:00.038
She knows.

34:05.877 --> 34:07.420
What...

34:10.256 --> 34:12.383
What is this?

34:15.386 --> 34:18.222
This does not

34:19.265 --> 34:22.185
happen to us.

35:04.811 --> 35:06.646
A private plane
       was chartered yesterday

35:06.687 --> 35:09.732
from Boeing Field in
     Seattle to Biggen Hill, UK.

35:09.732 --> 35:12.693
Paid for by Hatch Flood.
          They're in London.

35:12.693 --> 35:13.903
Flood. Say more.

35:13.945 --> 35:16.489
Los Alamos airport
        police report has him

35:16.489 --> 35:18.783
signed out to a Justin C. Falls.

35:18.783 --> 35:19.992
The same Justin C. Falls

35:19.992 --> 35:22.703
who was registered
         on that private jet.

35:22.745 --> 35:24.539
She has a DOE file.

35:24.580 --> 35:26.374
Stop. Her. Say more.

35:26.374 --> 35:27.416
Her file's sealed.

35:27.458 --> 35:29.252
If it's sealed, I want it.
   Get it. She could be an issue.

35:29.293 --> 35:31.754
Little bit of a learning curve
        with Sister Mary Lou.

35:31.796 --> 35:32.797
Apparently these...

35:32.797 --> 35:34.507
These guys aren't
       that great with women.

35:34.549 --> 35:36.008
Who was the third passenger?

35:36.050 --> 35:40.596
First initial K.
         Last name Faraday.

35:40.596 --> 35:42.223
It must be him, sir.

35:42.223 --> 35:43.474
Faraday.

35:44.809 --> 35:45.935
Book me a hotel in London.

35:45.977 --> 35:47.562
Make sure there's
        a change of clothes.

35:47.562 --> 35:48.813
-Oh, one more thing.
               -Yeah.

35:48.855 --> 35:50.982
I sourced background
           on Edward Flood.

35:50.982 --> 35:53.901
Apparently he had
       an arrangement with us

35:53.943 --> 35:55.736
dating back to 1978.

35:55.736 --> 35:57.530
The same year
         Newton disappeared.

35:57.572 --> 36:01.159
Stop. Say more.

36:05.705 --> 36:07.415
-Hey.

36:07.456 --> 36:09.000
Hey, what happened?

36:09.041 --> 36:13.629
He could not
         remember her name.

36:15.131 --> 36:17.175
It ripped him apart.

36:18.050 --> 36:19.510
Corroded him.

36:20.678 --> 36:22.346
Ate him alive.

36:23.097 --> 36:24.557
Like an infection.

36:26.642 --> 36:31.147
These are not
           my experiences.

36:32.565 --> 36:33.649
They're his.

36:35.401 --> 36:37.695
I cannot align it.

36:38.029 --> 36:39.906
I... I...

36:39.906 --> 36:43.534
I want it to stop.

36:43.576 --> 36:45.620
Wha-- What you're feeling...

36:45.620 --> 36:48.164
It's us.

36:48.998 --> 36:52.084
This is what we are.
               Humans.

36:52.084 --> 36:56.172
I do not have time...

36:57.757 --> 36:58.799
for this.

36:58.799 --> 37:01.594
Maybe you needed to
      understand him so that--

37:01.636 --> 37:04.764
Antheans understand each other.

37:04.805 --> 37:06.224
We do not...

37:06.974 --> 37:09.518
endure each other.

37:10.394 --> 37:11.437
We do.

37:13.689 --> 37:15.191
We do.

37:16.901 --> 37:19.612
The experiences of others,

37:19.654 --> 37:22.406
even strangers,
          we can feel them.

37:26.410 --> 37:27.536
How...

37:28.746 --> 37:30.206
do you...

37:30.790 --> 37:33.417
tolerate it?

37:33.876 --> 37:38.589
We... We tell ourselves stories

37:39.465 --> 37:40.758
to keep going.

37:41.968 --> 37:44.303
Deceptions.

37:44.595 --> 37:46.222
Sometimes.

37:47.556 --> 37:48.724
Creations.

37:50.810 --> 37:53.312
Imagination cuts both ways.

37:59.652 --> 38:02.571
If you try to get away from it,

38:03.781 --> 38:05.449
it's worse.

38:06.993 --> 38:11.622
That tree deformed itself,

38:12.498 --> 38:14.333
trying to survive.

38:16.460 --> 38:18.421
Was Newton

38:19.630 --> 38:21.507
deformed by humans?

38:22.091 --> 38:26.804
Why would
            he want me...

38:28.055 --> 38:30.266
to become like that?

38:34.812 --> 38:38.316
He wouldn't.

38:39.775 --> 38:41.819
Something must have...

38:43.821 --> 38:46.824
I have to finish the mission.

38:48.534 --> 38:49.827
Hey. Hey.

38:51.787 --> 38:52.997
Hey.

38:53.873 --> 38:56.500
Can you help me?

38:58.627 --> 38:59.670
Yeah.

39:29.575 --> 39:30.951
Where's your team?

39:30.951 --> 39:32.661
They'll be back.

39:32.661 --> 39:34.872
This is so messy, Hatch.

39:36.707 --> 39:37.875
Amateurish.

39:38.876 --> 39:40.127
That girl's a wreck.

39:40.169 --> 39:42.546
Call her "that girl"
            to her face.

39:42.588 --> 39:43.881
And Farady?

39:43.881 --> 39:45.383
Faraday.

39:45.841 --> 39:47.676
Skittish as a whippet.

39:47.676 --> 39:49.845
You know, he's a genius.

39:49.887 --> 39:52.431
He's like
    a once-in-a-lifetime meteor.

39:53.933 --> 39:55.726
Do you remember
       when this was painted?

39:57.728 --> 39:59.688
Of course.

39:59.688 --> 40:01.565
The glassed-in porch.

40:02.358 --> 40:05.528
I remember you read
    that book that whole summer.

40:09.073 --> 40:10.699
You practically slept with it.

40:11.992 --> 40:13.577
Dad gave it to me.

40:14.745 --> 40:16.705
Each animal had a job.

40:16.747 --> 40:18.457
Cats were teachers,

40:18.749 --> 40:19.959
dogs drove trucks.

40:20.000 --> 40:21.419
I remember.

40:21.836 --> 40:23.462
There were pigs.

40:24.755 --> 40:26.674
Do you remember what they did?

40:26.715 --> 40:27.758
No.

40:29.260 --> 40:31.387
The pigs were butchers.

40:32.638 --> 40:34.223
Ribs, bacon, beef.

40:34.223 --> 40:36.892
The pigs would
         carve up other pigs

40:36.892 --> 40:38.727
and sell them in pieces.

40:38.769 --> 40:40.563
Even to other pigs.

40:42.273 --> 40:44.400
You learn from a book like that.

40:45.359 --> 40:48.362
I remember you wouldn't
        look at the painter.

40:48.404 --> 40:51.615
I was afraid he was
     going to eat me. 

40:52.366 --> 40:54.076
But it didn't turn out
             to be him,

40:54.076 --> 40:55.786
it turned out to be you.

40:58.956 --> 41:01.459
Why do you need to
        feel like I hurt you?

41:07.173 --> 41:09.800
It reminds me I'm not a pig.

41:10.384 --> 41:13.596
I never called you that, Edie.
            That was Dad.

41:14.180 --> 41:15.431
What are you talking about?

41:15.431 --> 41:18.184
We both know who he was.

41:18.225 --> 41:20.269
But you gotta pretend
       like he was the saint,

41:20.269 --> 41:21.395
and I was the villain.

41:21.437 --> 41:22.688
I mean he was
       like Dr. Frankenstein,

41:22.730 --> 41:26.108
doing fucking Stanford Prison
 Experiments on his own daughter.

41:26.108 --> 41:28.444
I was an 11-year-old.

41:28.903 --> 41:30.821
All we ever had
           is each other.

41:32.323 --> 41:34.783
That's what makes
      your betrayal so fucked.

41:34.825 --> 41:36.160
Oh, look at yourself, Edie.

41:36.160 --> 41:37.912
I mean, uh, are you even eating?

41:37.912 --> 41:39.330
And he's been dead
          a bunch of years.

41:39.330 --> 41:41.040
I mean, you worry
         he's gonna show up

41:41.040 --> 41:42.875
and measure your upper arms
            after a bath?

41:42.917 --> 41:44.460
He was an ugly guy.

41:44.460 --> 41:45.878
He was ugly with you.

41:45.878 --> 41:47.379
He was doing ugly stuff at work,

41:47.421 --> 41:48.380
with the patents.

41:48.380 --> 41:49.423
You know, but you never
         wanted to hear it.

41:49.465 --> 41:51.175
Wait, this is about
            the patents?

41:52.343 --> 41:54.553
-This whole thing?
                -No.

41:54.553 --> 41:56.764
Oh, my God. To build this out,

41:56.764 --> 41:57.723
you need the patents.

41:57.765 --> 42:00.809
You've roped these people
        into your obsession!

42:00.851 --> 42:02.186
This is real. Okay?

42:02.228 --> 42:03.562
And Faraday is the only one

42:03.562 --> 42:05.397
who can unlock Newton's tenth.

42:05.397 --> 42:08.067
-You need this.
     -Get rid of the professor.

42:08.108 --> 42:09.318
We're not making
          the deal, Wyant.

42:09.360 --> 42:10.736
We're never making it.
            I don't care.

42:10.736 --> 42:13.030
There's
      someone here to see you.

42:13.072 --> 42:15.699
You need this. I don't.

42:23.832 --> 42:25.417
Wyant, what is this?

42:25.417 --> 42:27.586
I think it best
          if he tells you.

42:28.212 --> 42:30.589
And who is he?

42:31.215 --> 42:34.677
Edie,
        this is Spencer Clay.

42:35.135 --> 42:37.221
Wow.
          These grounds...

42:37.221 --> 42:39.557
It's just
         a perfect metaphor

42:39.598 --> 42:42.184
for the last gasps
      of the aristocracy, huh?

42:42.226 --> 42:44.311
Thank God for that.

42:44.311 --> 42:47.481
Handle whatever this is.
      I don't have time for it.

42:47.481 --> 42:49.984
Miss Flood,
        he can't handle this

42:49.984 --> 42:51.902
and you're not going anywhere.

42:52.570 --> 42:55.281
Call Robert and have him
     escorted off the property.

42:55.322 --> 42:56.407
He doesn't speak
          to me like that.

42:56.407 --> 42:58.909
I'm gonna speak to you
           any way I like.

43:01.078 --> 43:02.580
Hey, I don't know
        how much your father

43:02.580 --> 43:04.290
told you about his
         business dealings--

43:04.290 --> 43:06.250
He told me everything.
         We were very close.

43:06.250 --> 43:07.960
Oh, that is so nice. So were we.

43:08.002 --> 43:09.169
-Mm-hmm.
               -Yeah.

43:09.169 --> 43:11.922
And by we, I do mean
 the Central Intelligence Agency.

43:18.262 --> 43:19.221
No, that's...

43:19.263 --> 43:21.557
Oh, so, not everything.

43:21.890 --> 43:23.017
Okay.

43:23.058 --> 43:26.061
Listen, I need everybody
           to be optimal.

43:26.103 --> 43:28.063
So, it's important
      that you both understand

43:28.063 --> 43:31.650
that we installed
         your father, okay?

43:31.650 --> 43:35.404
I'm sure you've enjoyed
    believing that OriGen is a...

43:35.446 --> 43:38.073
family company.
        But, no. We took it.

43:38.073 --> 43:40.618
From a fellow named
           Thomas Newton.

43:40.951 --> 43:42.119
After we...

43:43.162 --> 43:44.246
took him apart--

43:44.288 --> 43:45.789
There's no confirmation--

43:45.789 --> 43:47.207
And then we installed
           your dad and...

43:47.207 --> 43:49.960
He was,
       I guess you'd call it,

43:49.960 --> 43:52.004
uh, a bag man.

43:52.796 --> 43:53.839
Doorman.

43:53.881 --> 43:54.965
He was a doorman.

43:54.965 --> 43:57.843
Meticulously selected for his

43:58.135 --> 43:59.845
mediocrity

43:59.887 --> 44:02.681
to mind a company
     that was of interest to us.

44:03.265 --> 44:05.601
But you... 

44:05.643 --> 44:06.685
Edie, those ten patents

44:06.685 --> 44:09.480
that you have just
       leveraged to the hilt--

44:09.521 --> 44:12.316
-No, you--
   -Yeah, those patents have been

44:12.358 --> 44:14.151
classified for years.
            They're ours.

44:15.361 --> 44:17.988
And because of our arrangement
           with your dad,

44:18.906 --> 44:20.324
well, now, so are you.

44:26.080 --> 44:27.122
Hey.

44:27.706 --> 44:30.918
Hey, I understand Mr. Faraday

44:30.959 --> 44:32.836
is here to make a deal.

44:33.837 --> 44:34.963
Yeah.

44:35.839 --> 44:38.342
Wyant, hmm?

44:40.010 --> 44:41.804
You're closing it today.

44:41.970 --> 44:43.347
Why?

44:43.389 --> 44:44.598
What do you know about him?

44:44.640 --> 44:47.893
I know he's,
        uh, well, brilliant.

44:49.353 --> 44:51.021
Also, he needs something
           that you have,

44:51.021 --> 44:52.523
to build something I want.

44:52.523 --> 44:54.566
And he's leading me
         to someone I want,

44:54.608 --> 44:57.986
and I intend to help him
      do both of those things.

44:58.404 --> 45:00.155
Okay? I have been

45:00.155 --> 45:04.743
charged with
       an almost sacred task.

45:05.452 --> 45:09.373
Mr. Faraday has become my duty.

45:11.208 --> 45:12.918
There's nothing
         in the way of that.

45:16.588 --> 45:17.881
Am I clear?

45:21.009 --> 45:22.052
Oh.

45:35.441 --> 45:38.402
Let's talk about Justin Falls.

45:47.202 --> 45:49.246
You need
       Newton's tenth patent,

45:49.288 --> 45:51.749
and Mr. Faraday is
      the key to unlocking it.

45:51.749 --> 45:56.128
Which Wyant has convinced me
     is beneficial for us both.

45:57.045 --> 46:00.007
But 85% is off the table.

46:00.007 --> 46:01.550
Oh, who's your friend?

46:01.592 --> 46:04.428
One of our consultants,
              Mr. Clay.

46:04.428 --> 46:06.054
-From?
        -Bayfield.

46:06.054 --> 46:09.266
Scientific application
     corporation, out of Weston.

46:09.266 --> 46:11.727
We're a DOE prime contractor.

46:12.269 --> 46:13.395
Bullshit.

46:13.437 --> 46:15.147
We're a global company.

46:15.189 --> 46:16.482
Once you guys come to terms,

46:16.482 --> 46:19.193
we can just fast-track you
   through regulations in 90 days.

46:19.193 --> 46:20.819
Greeks bearing gifts.

46:22.112 --> 46:23.405
What the fuck, Edie.

46:23.405 --> 46:25.574
I'll agree to 50%.

46:25.616 --> 46:27.409
-We need majority voting rights.
              -No way.

46:27.451 --> 46:30.454
You can have patent credit
       but only 5% royalties,

46:30.496 --> 46:31.914
since we're taking the risk

46:31.914 --> 46:33.081
and footing the bill
            for the labs.

46:33.123 --> 46:36.543
50% of stock options
   with a one-year vesting period.

46:36.585 --> 46:40.422
49% ownership and six years
          golden handcuffs.

46:40.422 --> 46:42.007
We'll need
       a silver bullet clause.

46:42.049 --> 46:44.468
-Fine.
              -"Fine"?

46:44.468 --> 46:47.679
Mr. Clay has contacts
             at the DOE.

46:47.679 --> 46:51.141
He's provided clarity
        on Miss Falls and...

46:53.143 --> 46:54.311
the gaps.

46:57.981 --> 46:59.024
And?

46:59.066 --> 46:59.942
She killed a man.

46:59.983 --> 47:03.445
Not "a man was killed."
          She killed a man.

47:03.445 --> 47:06.990
Her father, Josiah Falls,
      was present at the time.

47:07.032 --> 47:09.159
The gentleman's name
         was Daniel Holland.

47:09.159 --> 47:11.161
He was 28 years old.

47:14.289 --> 47:17.167
Holland was exposed
           to lethal doses

47:17.209 --> 47:18.585
of radiation under her watch

47:18.627 --> 47:20.963
during her experiments
     with fusion at Los Alamos.

47:20.963 --> 47:25.175
You knew the DOE had
    a mandatory evaluation period

47:25.175 --> 47:26.218
before you ran your tests,

47:26.260 --> 47:28.303
but you didn't wanna wait
         for their approval.

47:28.345 --> 47:29.972
You went in, after hours,

47:29.972 --> 47:31.849
even against
        your father's advice.

47:31.849 --> 47:35.310
You were described,
      Miss Falls, as reckless,

47:35.352 --> 47:36.812
negligent, even a zealot,

47:36.854 --> 47:40.566
which is not a word you find
    often in official documents.

47:40.607 --> 47:43.527
You were so singularly focused,

47:43.569 --> 47:46.029
you didn't realize the safety
        access system was off

47:46.071 --> 47:48.699
and you ran your
          experiments anyway.

47:48.740 --> 47:51.535
You pushed it and you cooked
          poor Mr. Holland.

47:53.078 --> 47:54.371
No.

47:56.039 --> 47:58.083
No, no! No!

47:58.083 --> 48:00.961
You made a decision
   that cost a young man his life,

48:01.003 --> 48:04.756
out of hubris and
   incomprehensibly poor judgment.

48:04.756 --> 48:07.342
That's in here, too, by the way.

48:08.343 --> 48:09.386
I agree to the terms,

48:09.428 --> 48:11.138
but I cannot put
          my money on her.

48:11.179 --> 48:13.056
She's out or I walk.

48:22.149 --> 48:23.859
Is this true?

48:24.568 --> 48:26.403
Yes.

48:27.237 --> 48:28.405
He was...

48:29.907 --> 48:34.995
irradiated and the file
             was sealed.

48:34.995 --> 48:36.997
Um...

48:36.997 --> 48:39.541
Uh, those were
       the term of settlement

48:39.541 --> 48:43.086
the DOE
        made with his family.

48:47.549 --> 48:50.302
What kind of radiation
             killed him?

48:50.302 --> 48:52.429
Uh, neutrons.

48:53.931 --> 48:57.351
So you did achieve fusion.

48:57.351 --> 48:58.894
Yes.

48:59.311 --> 49:01.271
-For how long?
               -Uh...

49:01.313 --> 49:03.482
Uh, ju...
         Just over a second.

49:03.523 --> 49:05.943
Beyond that
        would have been, um--

49:05.984 --> 49:07.903
-Impossible.

49:10.197 --> 49:11.949
Miss Falls...

49:13.575 --> 49:14.952
stays.

49:17.412 --> 49:18.956
Or I go.

49:19.122 --> 49:20.290
What?

49:26.630 --> 49:29.675
That doesn't speak highly of
     your judgment, Mr. Faraday.

49:29.716 --> 49:32.135
No, Miss Flood.

49:33.679 --> 49:36.306
It does not speak very highly...

49:37.474 --> 49:39.142
of yours.

49:43.105 --> 49:43.939
Uh...

49:43.939 --> 49:48.986
Oh! So, uh, you get
          me, him and her.

49:49.444 --> 49:51.321
Or you get nothing.

49:51.697 --> 49:53.365
And we all lose.

50:14.261 --> 50:16.346
Congratulations, all!

50:28.483 --> 50:29.860
Hey.

50:29.860 --> 50:31.570
I'm really looking forward to

50:31.611 --> 50:34.364
getting to know you,
            Mr. Faraday.

50:52.340 --> 50:53.550
Who's that guy?

51:00.390 --> 51:02.184
Welcome back to the world.

51:07.647 --> 51:09.399
You old fucker.

51:19.951 --> 51:22.037
I wanted it so bad.

51:22.746 --> 51:25.082
That's why I kept pushing.

51:27.793 --> 51:29.753
His hair fell out.

51:30.879 --> 51:33.799
His teeth... 

51:33.840 --> 51:35.592
He vomited them up.

51:38.887 --> 51:42.432
After he died, I...
     I found out I was pregnant.

51:43.809 --> 51:45.435
Daniel Holland

51:46.686 --> 51:49.106
is Molly's father.

51:49.564 --> 51:50.774
Yeah.

51:52.234 --> 51:54.778
You know, I didn't leave
    my room during the pregnancy

51:54.820 --> 51:56.488
except to go to the doctor.

51:57.781 --> 51:59.616
I thought if I did,

51:59.658 --> 52:02.077
something bad would happen.

52:02.661 --> 52:05.580
I'd be punished. 

52:06.832 --> 52:09.793
I had Molly at home in the tub.

52:10.085 --> 52:11.795
Never left her side.

52:12.420 --> 52:13.505
I didn't sleep.

52:15.340 --> 52:17.259
I just watched her

52:18.510 --> 52:19.636
for a year.

52:20.512 --> 52:22.139
I was waiting.

52:23.348 --> 52:27.310
I thought
       we'd both be punished.

52:29.646 --> 52:32.190
But we weren't.

52:34.693 --> 52:36.319
She's perfect.

52:39.698 --> 52:42.033
But my dad is...

52:42.033 --> 52:44.661
Sometimes I think
        maybe he was instead.

52:49.749 --> 52:52.294
She looks just like her father.

52:55.505 --> 52:57.340
And she doesn't know anything.

53:01.136 --> 53:04.347
I can't do anything for them
        after what I've done.

53:05.056 --> 53:09.686
Except try to save
      the entire fucking world.

53:11.605 --> 53:13.356
Maybe then, they'll be safe.

53:15.317 --> 53:16.526
From me.

53:19.988 --> 53:21.865
So I'm grateful to you

53:22.866 --> 53:24.868
for not cutting me out.

53:24.910 --> 53:27.662
If we are going to continue,

53:27.662 --> 53:30.040
I need you to understand

53:30.040 --> 53:32.167
that your perspective is skewed.

53:32.209 --> 53:37.797
The nature of progress
   is that it requires sacrifice.

53:37.839 --> 53:40.383
You achieved fusion.

53:41.218 --> 53:42.802
That only one person died

53:42.844 --> 53:46.181
during one of the greatest
         evolutionary steps

53:46.181 --> 53:51.228
on your timeline is what
      you would call a miracle.

53:51.519 --> 53:52.229
Yeah.

53:52.229 --> 53:56.274
Somehow, you see it
            as a failure.

53:57.776 --> 53:59.444
You succeeded.

54:00.320 --> 54:05.408
Do you remember
   what I said when we first met?

54:06.618 --> 54:09.579
Your mission is my mission.

54:10.163 --> 54:14.251
Neither one of us
          can go forward...

54:16.378 --> 54:17.420
alone.
